Why AGPL-3.0-or-later (interim stance, see LICENSE-INTENT.md):

myc is one of three federated substrates (omega, liquid, myc) plus a
meta-coordination layer (trinity) that together form a mycelium-style
cognitive ecosystem. The substrate's value is its position in this
federation, not the source alone. The AGPL-3.0-or-later license is chosen
as a STOPGAP to protect that federation from extractive forks:

  - Anyone may study, modify, and use myc.
  - Anyone who runs a modified myc as a network-accessible service must
    publish their modifications (AGPLv3 §13).
  - This prevents closed proprietary forks from capturing the mycelium
    while still allowing academic study and personal research.

A custom mycelium-aware license is planned. Until it is drafted and
adopted, AGPL-3.0-or-later is the closest existing licence to that intent.

